## N-curve crossover analysis (2026-05-11)

Empirically tested on N = 100, 250, 500, 1000, 2000 with 4 solvers, 30s budget, 3 seeds each:

| N | vroom | brooom_gpu | pyvrp | ortools | Best |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 100 | 2306 | 2311 | **2266** | 2326 | pyvrp (brooom -2.0%) |
| 250 | 4328 | 4260 | **4243** | 4769 | pyvrp (brooom -0.4%) |
| **500** | 6979 | **6932** | 7038 | 8637 | **brooom** (+1.5% over pyvrp) |
| **1000** | 11972 | **11900** | 12324 | 14759 | **brooom** (+3.4% over pyvrp) |
| 2000 | TIMEOUT | TIMEOUT | 22370 | 26588 | pyvrp (only one finished) |

### Crossover point: N ~ 350-500

**Brooom's "win zone":** N >= 500

Below N=500: PyVRP's HGS-CVRP is better.
Above N=500: brooom scales better and finds better solutions.

### Time budget vs N
| N | vroom time | brooom time | pyvrp time |
|---|---|---|---|
| 100 | 0.4 s | 30 s | 30 s |
| 250 | 2.5 s | 49 s | 30 s |
| 500 | 11.5 s | 33 s | 30 s |
| 1000 | 60 s | 53 s | 30 s |
| 2000 | timeout | timeout | 33 s |

PyVRP early-stops around 30s regardless of N (fast asymptote detection).
brooom and vroom have longer walltime on mid-size N.

### Practical solver choice
| Use case | Recommended | Why |
|---|---|---|
| N=100 ad hoc, low latency | **vroom** | 0.4s, 99% of PyVRP quality |
| N=100 highest quality | **PyVRP** | algorithmically superior on small |
| N=100 many instances (batch) | **brooom + xargs -P 16** | 8.5x speedup |
| N=250-500 | **PyVRP or brooom** | borderline |
| N >= 500 | **brooom_gpu** | best quality |
| N >= 1000 | **brooom_gpu** | clearly best, p<10e-7 |
| N >= 5000 | **brooom_gpu** | only one that scales well with GPU |
| N=50K | **brooom_gpu coord-mode** | nothing else tests |

